Its psychological effect, I imagine, was inferior to that of Virgil’s picture, if only because the Roman poet set himself to support with all his gifts the definite Italian policy of Augustus,3 at a time when Italy's need for national satisfaction and hope were greater than they had ever yet been.

This, Ι think, was the poet’s primary motive‚ but in the execution he was confronted by serious diffi- culties which made his task a complex one. We have to remember that all the peoples of. the proces- sion were the enemies of the Trojans, and summoned to resist the establishment in Italy of Aeneas and his host, and therein also to resist the decrees of Fate which were to make Rome eventually the mistress of Italy.
